Clackson et al., Nature, 352: 624-628 (1991
).






Repertoires of synthetically rearranged V genes can be derived in vitro from V gene segments. Most of the human VH-gene segments have been cloned and sequenced (reported in 
Tomlinson et al., J. Mol. Biol., 227: 776-798 (1992
)), and mapped (reported in 
Matsuda et al., Nature Genet., 3: 88-94 (1993
); these cloned segments (including all the major conformations of the H1 and H2 loop) can be used to generate diverse VH gene repertoires with PCR primers encoding H3 loops of diverse sequence and length as described in Hoogenboom and 
Winter, J. Mol. Biol., 227: 381-388 (1992
). VH repertoires can also be made with all the sequence diversity focussed in a long H3 loop of a single length as described in 
Barbas et al., Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 89: 4457-4461 (1992
